        <p>
            <strong><a name="cp3"></a>Chinese Silk Paintings</strong><br>
            The art of painting on silk goes back for centuries. Silk has a  strength, durability, and texture that makes it an excellent choice for watercolor painting.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong><a name="cd8"></a>Chinese Rice Paper Paintings</strong><br>
            Rice paper was developed centuries ago in China and Japan for the purpose of calligraphy and brush painting. It is particularly durable, with a distinctive texture and a slight translucency, that is perfect for displaying dynamic strokes.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong><a name="cd4"></a>Chinese Shikishi Paintings</strong><br>
            Paintings are created on Washi paper that has been mounted onto gold trim art
            board. This process produces paintings that do not need framing and come ready
            to be displayed in your home.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong><a name="cp5"></a>Lingnan School of Painting</strong><br>
            The Lingnan School of Chinese painting stresses renewal and creativity. Its style, developed in
            China circa 1900, combines traditional Chinese Painting with elements of
            Western and Japanese realism.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong><a name="cp6"></a>Chinese Painting Condition</strong><br>
            Our Chinese paintings are in excellent condition but we include the following information to avoid any misunderstandings. Silk paintings are rolled and properly backed for mounting and framing. Because of their unique texture, there are some minor details to expect when receiving a painting:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                We do not offer paintings with major creases or tears, however some of the corners and edges might be mildly creased and/or torn. These can easily be cut or matted and do not detract from the painting itself.
            <li>
                The nature of water paint in some instance causes minor color variations that may not be noticeable on the pictures we post. This is not a result of a mistake or mishandling, but rather a natural characteristic of the art.
            </li>
        </ol>
